8.6 Œºs

Markov Decision Problems (MDPs)

  • Assume a finite set of states S

  • A finite set of actions A

  • For state s‚ààS and action a‚ààA we can compute the cost or the contribution C(s,a)

  • There is a transition matrix pt(St+1|St,at) which tells us with which probability we go from state St to St+1 upen taking decision at

  • Even though many problems have continuous state and action spaces, this is a very useful class of problems to study.

1.4 ms

Optimality (Bellman) Equations

  • But let's start with no uncertainty. If we are at state St, we know how St+1 will look like with certainty if we choose a certain action at

  • Then we just choose the best action:

at‚àó(St)=arg‚Å°maxat‚ààAt(Ct(St,at)+Œ≤Vt+1(St+1(St,at)))

  • The associated value of this choice is then the same Bellman Equation we know from last time,

Vt(St)=maxat‚ààAt(Ct(St,at)+Œ≤Vt+1(St+1(St,at)))=Ct(St,at‚àó(St))+Œ≤Vt+1(St+1(St,at‚àó(St)))

15.5 Œºs

Enter Uncertainty

  • Uncertainty comes into play if we don't know exactly what state St+1 we'll end up in.

  • We may have partial information on the likelihood of each state occuring, like a belief, or prior information.

  • We have our transition matrix pt(St+1|St,at), and can define the standard form of the Bellman Equation:

Vt(St)=maxat‚ààAt(Ct(St,at)+Œ≤‚àës‚Ä≤‚ààSpt(St+1=s‚Ä≤|St,at)Vt+1(s‚Ä≤))

10.9 Œºs

  • we can also write it more general without the summation

Vt(St)=maxat‚ààAt(Ct(St,at)+Œ≤E[Vt+1(St+1(St,at))|St])

9.1 Œºs

Policy Iteration

  • In most economic contexts, there is more structure on a problem.

  • In our consumption example, we know that the Euler Equation must hold.

  • Sometimes there are other optimality conditions that one could leverage.

  • In our case, we have this equation at an optimal policy c‚àó(Rt):

u‚Ä≤(c‚àó(Rt))=Œ≤E[u‚Ä≤(c(Rt+1))]=Œ≤E[u‚Ä≤(Rt‚àíc‚àó(Rt)+y)]

  • So: We just have to find the function c‚àó(Rt)!

10.4 Œºs

Just?

  • There is a slight issue here. The Euler Equation in itself does not enforce the contraint that we cannot borrow any R.

  • In particular, Rt‚â•0 is missing from the above equation.

  • look back above at the last plot of the consumption function. It has a kink!

  • The Euler Equation applies only to the right of that kink!

  • If tomorrow's consumption is low (we are saving a lot), today's consumption is relatively high, implying that we consume more than we have in terms of Rt.

  • Satisfying the Euler Equation would require to set Rt<0 sometimes, which is ruled out.

9.5 Œºs

  • So if we want to use the Euler Equation, we need to manually adjust for that.

  • üò©

  • Alright, let's do it. It's not too bad in the end.

  • First, let's put down the marginal utility function and it's inverse:

  • We need the inverse of the marginal utility function?

  • Yes. Here is why. For any candidate consumption level ct

u‚Ä≤(ct)=Œ≤E[u‚Ä≤(c(Rt+1))]u‚Ä≤(ct)=RHS

  • So, if we have computed the RHS, current period optimal consumption is just

ct=(u‚Ä≤)‚àí1(RHS)(EEresid)

where (u‚Ä≤)‚àí1(z) denotes the inverse of function u‚Ä≤(x).

Example

  • Suppose tomorrow's consumption function does have the kink at Rt+1=1.5

  • I.e. ct+1‚àó(Rt+1)=Rt+1,‚àÄRt+1‚â§1.5

  • Let yt+1=1.5,Rt=1. Now try out consumption choice ct=1!

Rt+1=Rt‚àíct+yt+1=1‚àí1+1.5=1.5‚áíct+1‚àó(1.5)=1.5

because right at the kink!

  • Then, the Euler equation says:

u‚Ä≤(ct)=u‚Ä≤(ct+1)ct=(u‚Ä≤)‚àí1(u‚Ä≤(ct+1))ct=ct+1=1.5

  • Well, that in turn means that Rt‚àíct=1‚àí1.5<0, i.e. we would have to borrow 0.5 units of R in order to satisfy that Euler Equation!

Infinite Time Problems

  • Let's now introduce the infinite time version of this.

  • For that purpose, let's rely on the well known Optimal Growth model:

V(k)=max0<k‚Ä≤<f(k)u(f(k)‚àík‚Ä≤)+Œ≤V(k‚Ä≤)f(k)=kŒ±k0 given

  • The solution in finite time was simple by going backwards.

  • Here, we need to rely on results from Functional Analysis: Remember the Contraction Mapping Theorem?

  • The Contraction Mapping Theorem or the Banache Fixed Point Theoreom says there is a unique fixed point in an appropriately chosen function space. We arrive at it from an arbitrary starting point by just iterating on the operator T(V) until V=T(V)
